        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2208189952" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12833080221508526996">Wonderful Life is pretty, well, wonderful. If your curiosity about the Burgess Shale or the weird and wonderful beings of the Cambrian period needs sating, this book should more than do it. It is quite dense — Gould may have been a popular science writer, but he didn’t dumb it down — but it’s worth the time investment.<br/><br/>It’s true that some of the reconstructions of these beings have been challenged since Gould wrote, but it’s still worth reading for his overall theory about the development of life</span>
  <span id="freeText12833080221508526996" style="display:none">Wonderful Life is pretty, well, wonderful. If your curiosity about the Burgess Shale or the weird and wonderful beings of the Cambrian period needs sating, this book should more than do it. It is quite dense — Gould may have been a popular science writer, but he didn’t dumb it down — but it’s worth the time investment.<br /><br />It’s true that some of the reconstructions of these beings have been challenged since Gould wrote, but it’s still worth reading for his overall theory about the development of life, and much important (and correct) detail about the Burgess Shale.<br /><br /><a href="https://breathesbooks.com/2018/03/06/review-wonderful-life/" rel="nofollow noopener">Reviewed for The Bibliophibian.</a></span>
